<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-820-452  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 820 452.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Oct 30 1989 n243 p92(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How IT contributes to the greenhouse effect. (computer andcommunications equipment manufacturing plays a role in thedepletion of the ozone layer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hoffman, Thomas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>According to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), theelectronics industry accounts for about 12 percent ofchlorofluorocarbons (CFC) usage in the US and 17 percent of the390 billion pounds of CFCs that pollute the atmosphere worldwide.andO;IBM's manufacturing plant in Endicott, NY is the single largestemitter of CFCs in the US while its San Jose plant ranks third.andO;ATandamp;T is the fifth largest emitter on a corporate-wide basis, nextto General Motors Corp, United Technologies Corp, IBM, and GeneralElectric Co. In efforts to reduce CFC pollution, the Bushadministration has enacted legislation based on the Helsinkideclaration that imposes a worldwide ban on CFC emissions by thenext century.andP;  Companies such as IBM and ATandamp;T have also beenforced to seek viable alternatives to CFCs in manufacturing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryCommunications IndustryEcologyManufacturingChlorofluorocarbonsEnvironmental Protection.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>